'''Mary "Mimi" Gates''' ([[née]] '''Gardner'''; born July 30, 1943)<ref>United States Public Record Number 485370969</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[art historian]] who is the recent Director of the [[Seattle Art Museum]]. In 1996, she married [[Bill Gates Sr.]], father of [[Bill Gates]].
==Career== Gates holds a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] degree in art history from [[Stanford University]], a certificate with honors in [[Chinese language]] and [[culture of China|culture]] from the [[École Nationale des Langues Orientales Vivantes]] in [[Paris]], an [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] degree in Oriental and Chinese Studies from the [[University of Iowa]], and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] degree in Art History from [[Yale University]]. An old friend of [[Theresa Heinz Kerry]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/connelly/214744_joel07.html |title=Teresa Heinz Kerry hasn't lost her outspoken way |author=Joel Connelly |date=March 7, 2005 |accessdate=2006-09-08}}</ref> she is also a frequent juror for the [[Heinz Awards]], appointed by the Heinz Family Philanthropies to award outstanding achievement in the area of Arts and Humanities.<ref>[http://www.heinzawards.net/jurors.asp Heinz Awards]</ref>
She was curator of Asian art and then director of the [[Yale University Art Gallery]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=travel&res=9A04E4D91438F932A05750C0A963948260 ''New York Times''], March 31, 1985.</ref> At Yale, she contributed to the development of the Association of Art Museum Directors (AAMD) guideline discouraging the sale of artwork in a Museum's collection, even to cover operating costs. In a brief, she detailed her view that museum collections are ''"a public trust"''.<ref>Jen Graves, [http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/Content?oid=55935 "In Art News: Sunshine, Please"], ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]'', August 24–30, 2006.</ref> She has also lobbied the U.S. and [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] negotiators to ensure that implementation of [[UNESCO]] rules about non-archaeological cultural exports do not tie the hands of American curators.<ref>[http://www.aamd.org/advocacy/documents/MimiGates.pdf Letter to the President’s Cultural Advisory Committee on behalf of the AAMD] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001163807/http://www.aamd.org/advocacy/documents/MimiGates.pdf |date=2006-10-01 }}</ref>
She came to Seattle in 1994 to head the museum, and in her tenure, has added over 2500 works to the collections.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://podcasts.thestranger.com/2007/11/invisible_mimi_gates |title = What Mimi Gates Loves |author = Jen Graves |publisher = ''The Stranger'' |date = November 6, 2007 |accessdate = 2007-11-07 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071208201525/http://podcasts.thestranger.com/2007/11/invisible_mimi_gates |archivedate = December 8, 2007 |df = }}</ref> Among these are many Asian art treasures and works by [[Van Dyck]], [[Albert Bierstadt]], [[Richard Serra]] and [[Alexander Calder]]. The museum has also established a [[sculpture park]]. The museum's endowment has tripled to over $75 million and the region's first conservation studio was opened.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/visualart/217823_mimigates.html |title=Mimi Gates, Seattle Art Museum's director, doesn't shy away from a challenge |author=Regina Hackett |publisher=''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' |date=March 29, 2005 |accessdate=2006-09-03}}</ref> In 1999, the museum discovered that a [[Matisse]] painting in its possession was [[Nazi plunder|looted by Nazis]] and owned by the descendants of French-Jewish art dealer [[Paul Rosenberg (art dealer)|Paul Rosenberg]]. Gates brokered an 11th-hour settlement that returned the artwork, after which the museum sued the gallery that had sold it the painting in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aamd.org/newsroom/r061499.php |title=SAM to Return Matisse Odalisque to Rosenbergs |publisher=[[Association of Art Museum Directors]] |date=June 14, 1999 |accessdate=2006-09-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001164136/http://www.aamd.org/newsroom/r061499.php |archivedate=October 1, 2006 |df= }}</ref> Gates has co-authored ''Porcelain Stories: From China to Europe'' <ref>Julie Emerson, Jennifer Chen, Mimi Gardner Gates ''Porcelain Stories: From China to Europe'' 2000, University of Washington Press {{ISBN|0-932216-52-8}}</ref> and ''Biblical Art and the Asian Imagination''<ref>Patricia C. Pongracz, John W. Cook, Mimi Gates, Ena Heller ''Biblical Art and the Asian Imagination'' 2005, D Giles Ltd. {{ISBN|1-904832-18-0}}</ref>
Gates retired from the Seattle Art Museum in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://artdaily.com/news/24560/Mimi-Gates-Announces-Retirement-as-Director-of-the-Seattle-Art-Museum |title=Mimi Gates Announces Retirement as Director of the Seattle Art Museum |publisher = ''ArtDaily'' |accessdate=2018-09-09 }}</ref>
Gates, elected by Yale alumni, served a six-year term, commencing July 1, 2007, on the [[Yale Corporation]], [[Yale University]]’s governing body.
