{{Infobox person | name = Ricky Lauren | ethnicity = | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1943|6|15}} | birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | death_date = |birth_name = Ricky Ann Loew-Beer | death_place = | nationality = {{USA}} | alma_mater = [[Hunter College]] | employer = | occupation = Author, artist, photographer | title = | spouse = {{marriage|[[Ralph Lauren]]|1964}} | children = 3, including [[Dylan Lauren|Dylan]] and [[David Lauren]] }}
'''Ricky Lauren''' (born ''' Ricky Ann Low-Beer''' on June 15, 1943), is an American author, artist and photographer and wife of fashion designer [[Ralph Lauren]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/American-Icon-Ralph-Lauren-and-His-Fascinating-Family_2 |title= American Icon Ralph Lauren and His Family |work=Oprah Show |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> She is also a psychotherapist.<ref name="PW The Hamptons">{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-1182-9327-0 | title=The Hamptons: Food, Family, and History|website=Publishers Weekly|date=April 16, 2012 |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref>
==Early life== Born Ricky Ann Low-Beer, she grew up in [[New York City]].<ref name="GRL" /> She is the daughter of Austrian immigrants, Margaret Vytouch and Rudolph Low-Beer.<ref name="AD" /><ref name="CT cowgirl">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-03-18/features/0703180373_1_chilean-sea-bass-sunflowers-chocolate|title=Ricky Lauren's 10 Favorite Things|date=March 18, 2007|author=Lisa Cregan|accessdate=December 17, 2016 }}</ref> Lauren was an English major at [[Hunter College]]. She met her future husband Ralph Lauren at the eye doctor's office where she was working part-time. Lauren also taught fifth grade and danced for a time in [[The Bronx]].<ref name="GRL" /> On December 20, 1964, she married Ralph Lauren in New York City.<ref name="AD" />
==Career== ===Hostess, patron and fundraiser=== Lauren has supported her husband's career as a kind of "silent partner", as summarized by ''The New York Times''.<ref name="Polo Persona" /> These activities included attending fashion industry events or charities with him,<ref name="Polo Persona" /><ref name="PM" /> hosting parties,<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/7891368/valley_news/ | title=Ms. Fontanne on the Town 'Every Night: City lights| author=Liz Smith |newspaper=Valley News |location=Van Nuys, California | date=October 7, 1977 | page=77 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> and her patronage for charitable events.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://newspaperarchive.com/jm/kingston/kingston/kingston-gleaner/clippings/Celebrity/142439/ |title=Lavish Affair at the annual Round Hill Carnival|newspaper=Kingston Gleaner|location=Kingston, Jamaica | date=February 19, 2002 |page=33 | author=Janet Silvera|via=NewspaperARCHIVE|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref> In 2000, she and her husband established a cancer center which is part of [[North General Hospital]] in [[Harlem]]. The couple also founded the Ralph and Ricky Lauren Center for the Performing Arts, which is located at the [[Lexington School for the Deaf]], in New York City.{{sfn|Mattern|2013|p=72}}
Lauren has been identified as the "Polo Persona", the model by which the Polo advertising campaigns are developed.<ref name="Polo Persona" /> Of being his muse, Ralph wrote in his memoir, "I didn't like the girl with all the makeup and high heels. I liked the girl in jeans and a white shirt with rolled-up sleeves, wearing her boyfriend's jacket. That's the girl I am attracted to. That's the girl I married—Ricky."<ref name="HB Natural beauty" /> Ralph also acknowledged that when he began designing women's clothes, his interest was piqued by his wife's frustration in finding clothes she would like that could fit her slim and petite build.{{sfn|Mattern|2013|p=40}}
===Psychotherapist=== After her children were in school, Lauren returned to college and got her degree and then worked as a psychotherapist.<ref name="PM">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.port-magazine.com/fashion/the-enduring-icon-ralph-lauren/|title=The Enduring Icon: Ralph Lauren|magazine=Port Magazine| author=Donald Morrison | number=14|date=November 17, 2014|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>
===Author=== Lauren is an author, artist and photographer most prominently known for her lifestyle and cookbooks.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.vogue.com/970159/the-launch-of-ricky-laurens-new-book/ |title= The Launch of Ricky Lauren’s New Book |work=Vogue |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2149420/How-entertain-like-socialite-Ralph-Laurens-wife-Ricky-shares-recipes-dinner-party-tips-new-book.html |title= American Icon Ralph Lauren and His Family |work=The Daily Mail |date=2012-05-25 |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> One of her books is ''Cuisine, Lifestyle, and Legend of the Double RL Ranch'',<ref name="NYT Stay at Homes" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Cuisine, Lifestyle, and Legend of the Double RL Ranch|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oBNYLwEACAAJ|year=2012|publisher=Melcher Media, Inc.|isbn=978-1-59591-075-2}}</ref> of which ''[[The New York Times]]'' says, "Here is a loving — and really beautiful — picture-book tribute (with history and recipes) to the spot near Telluride that spawned an empire built on denim shirts, tooled turquoise-buckle belts, and red-and-black horse blankets."<ref name="NYT Stay at Homes" /> It reflects her interest in a casual life style and simple Western-style cuisine.<ref name="CT cowgirl" /> She wrote ''[[The Hamptons: Food, Family and History]]'',<ref name="PW The Hamptons" /><ref>{{cite book|title=[[The Hamptons: Food, Family and History]]|year=2012|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=978-1-118-29327-0}}</ref> which was well received by ''[[Publishers Weekly]]''.<ref name="PW The Hamptons" /> Lauren wrote and illustrated "Safari" with her photographs from a 1983 trip to Africa. The proceeds of the leather-and canvas-bound book go to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature|World Wildlife Fund]].<ref name="Polo Persona">{{cite web |url= http://articles.latimes.com/1990-05-30/news/vw-235_1_ralph-lauren|title= The Polo Persona : Fashion: For Ricky Lauren, epitome of the Ralph Lauren look, now is the time to pursue personal projects--including a new book |date=1990-05-30 |website= Los Angeles Times |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> She also wrote the book ''My Island'' in 1994.<ref>{{ cite book | title=My Island | publisher=Random House, Incorporated | year= 1994 | isbn=978-0-679-43711-6}}</ref>
==Personal life== Ricky and Ralph Lauren have three children, Andrew, [[David Lauren|David]], and [[Dylan Lauren|Dylan]].<ref name="[[The Wall Street Journal]] " />{{efn|She ensured that they had chores and helped her with activities like meal preparation and grocery shopping, to ensure that they had a down-to-earth lifestyle.<ref name="HB Natural beauty">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.harpersbazaar.com/magazine/feature-articles/ricky-lauren-interview-0612|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411060213/http://www.harpersbazaar.com/magazine/feature-articles/ricky-lauren-interview-0612|title=Ricky Lauren: Natural Beauty | magazine=Harper's Bazaar|date= | archivedate=April 11, 2013 | accessdate=December 17, 2016 }}</ref> Andrew (born 1969) is a film producer and actor.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://observer.com/2008/04/andrew-lauren-son-of-ralph-worships-redford-beatty-welles/ |website=New York Observer | title=Andrew Lauren, Son of Ralph, Worships Redford, Beatty, Welles | author= Irina Aleksander | date=April 30, 2008 |accessdate=December 15, 2016}}</ref> David (born 1971) is Executive Vice President of Global Advertising, Marketing, and Communications at [[Ralph Lauren Corporation]]. In September 2011, he married [[Lauren Bush]], the granddaughter of former President [[George H. W. Bush]].<ref name="[[The Wall Street Journal]] ">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-day-in-the-life-of-david-lauren-1443630691?mg=id-wsj |title=A Day in the Life of David Lauren |author=Christopher Ross |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |publisher=News Corp |date=2015-09-30 |accessdate=2016-05-09}}</ref> Dylan (born 1974) is owner of [[Dylan's Candy Bar]] in New York City. In June 2011, she married hedge fund manager, Paul Arrouet.<ref name="[[The New York Times]] ">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/12/fashion/weddings/dylan-lauren-paul-arrouet-weddings.html |title=Dylan Lauren and Paul Arrouet |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2011-06-10 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref>}} The Laurens lived in [[Southampton, New York]]<ref name="NYDN" /> in a converted barn during the beginning of their marriage.<ref name="Newsday">{{cite news | url=http://www.newsday.com/lifestyle/home-and-garden/ricky-lauren-likes-a-lived-in-look-for-her-hamptons-homes-1.3741969 | title=Ricky Lauren likes a lived-in look for her Hamptons homes|date=May 25, 2012|agency=Associated Press|website=Newsday | accessdate=December 17, 2016 }}</ref> Then, they spent the summers in [[Long Island]].<ref name="NYDN">{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/eats/ricky-lauren-wife-designer-ralph-lauren-reveals-beloved-family-recipes-hamptons-article-1.1093365 | title=Ricky Lauren, wife of designer Ralph Lauren, reveals beloved family recipes in 'The Hamptons'|website=New York Daily News | date=June 17, 2012 | author=Ricky Lee | accessdate=December 17, 2016 }}</ref> They had two houses in [[Amagansett, New York|Amagansett]], from which Ralph commuted into [[New York City]], and then a house in [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton]].<ref name="Newsday" /> She currently resides in New York City, [[Montauk, New York|Montauk]], New York, Jamaica, and on the family owned Double RL Ranch beneath the [[San Juan Mountains]] outside [[Telluride, Colorado]]<ref name="Polo Persona" /><ref name="AD">{{cite web |url= http://www.architecturaldigest.com/gallery/ralph-lauren-colorado-ranch-slideshow/all |title= Ralph Lauren’s Colorado Ranch |date=2002-08-31 |work=Architectural Digest |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> that they bought in 1982.<ref name="NYT Stay at Homes">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/07/garden/07books.html | title=Getaways for Stay-at-Homes | author=Penelope Green | date=December 7, 2006 | website=The New York Times | accessdate=December 15, 2016}}</ref>
Lauren studied photography after she was married.<ref name="GRL">{{cite web |url= http://global.ralphlauren.com/en-us/Magazine/Editorial/sum12/Pages/rickylauren.aspx?|title= Ricky Lauren |work=Ralph Lauren |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref>
